                            <div class="container">
                    <div class="exc-container">
                        <div class="muscle-text bd-bot exercise-list-start">
                            <h3><b>Clavicular Head</b></h3><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The </span><a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK525991/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener"><span style="font-weight: 400;">pectoralis major clavicular head</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> is the upper fibers of the chest, located just below the collarbone. </span></p><p><a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7579505/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Evidence</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> indicates an incline bench press at a 30° angle, has the greatest level of clavicular activation compared to the horizontal bench.  </span></p><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">This portion of the chest originates from the anterior surface of the clavicle and inserts into the humerus. During the incline dumbbell bench press, these fibers contract to perform the pressing and lowering phases of the movement. </span></p>                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                                        <section class="exc-secondary">
                <div class="container">
                    <div class="exc-container bd-bot">
                        <div class="muscle-title">
